dataIdInfo.idAbs:
The creation of decadal land cover data sets was a two-step procedure. The first step satisfied the assumption that Reclamation Districts represented potentially reclaimed wetland or swampland. To this end the pre-development land cover was filtered to just the Permanent Wetland, Seasonal Wetland, and Vernal Pool categories prior to intersection with the Reclamation Districts formed prior to or within that decade. The result was the same extent as the original Permanent Wetland/Seasonal Wetland/Vernal Pool data but with some portion converted to Potentially Reclaimed land. This intersected layer was then combined with the remaining predevelopment land cover prior to the second step.

In the second step the first step output was intersected with the previously developed irrigated area polygons to form the final land cover data set for that decade. The irrigated lands supersede all other classes including potentially reclaimed land since they are based on the most defensible data. This process was then repeated for each decade. The result is a flat, unambiguous spatial coverage. In the case of the 1860 data there was no change from the predevelopment state as no Reclamation Districts were formed and there was little evidence for any significant irrigation activity.
dataIdInfo.idPurp:
These data were developed as part of a decadal data set of landcover representations for the period 1850 to 1920. Multiple sources of inputs were considered but primarily a geo-spatial representation of the Phyllis Fox work from 2015 (http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/19/4257/2015/). The data are meant to support modeling efforts by UC Berkeley.
MWH developed eight (8) decadal land use descriptions that document the generalized spatial conversion of land use due to (a) wetland reclamation activities and (b) development of land for irrigated agriculture.
The total acreages and spatial extents of reclaimed lands were based on readily available information about the spatial extents of reclamation districts, DWR records that indicate the date of each district’s formation, and on DWR documentation of land reclamation activities in the Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta (Delta).
Mostly, total county acreages of irrigated land were based on county-specific census information for irrigated agriculture dating back to 1850. Prior to 1880 evidence for large scale irrigation was anecdotal and often contradictory. For 1880, acreages were based on historical documentation of statewide irrigated agriculture and an interpolation between county-specific census information from neighboring decades. The spatial extents of irrigated land was based on available spatial descriptions of irrigated agriculture from 1934 (USFS 1934) and 1912 (USDA 1913). The spatial extents of irrigated land for each decade were created by using these descriptions of irrigated land and applying a county-by-county negative buffer. The application of a “negative buffer” reduces the acreage of all polygons in a given county by relocating the outer boundary of each polygon by a uniform distance toward the centroid of each polygon: the distance of the relocation was determined by the amount of adjustment needed to match the census-based tabulated county-specific irrigated acreages in a given decade.
In summary, more information was found to be readily available than anticipated at the beginning of the project. The quality of information available and the timeframe for this study did not allow for a parcel-by-parcel reconstruction of specific agricultural practices and the spatial extents used in this study should not be interpreted as a definitive reconstruction of specific agricultural parcel uses. However, the development of parcel-by-parcel reconstructions are not required for generalized, lumped parameter hydrological simulation tools. This study provides spatial information that will be accurate for the parameterization of such hydrology models, and is robust enough to be applied across multiple models with differing element/grid delineations. The accuracy of the representation provided by this study meets its purpose, which is to improve the understanding how land use development in the Central Valley influenced the hydrologic processes in both the Delta and its major tributaries.

Consts.useLimit:
NOTE:

1. Source irrigated area polygons were intersected with the decade-appropriate county boundaries and then iteratively reduced in size until the census reported aceages for that county and decade were reached to +-50 acres. This results in a couple of artifacts of which the user should be aware. Mainly, irrigated boundaries pull away from the county boundaries during this process. As county boundaries often follow hydrologic features, this results in an underrepresentation of irrigated land along such areas. Secondly, due to the fact that data are derived from a common source, but the county boundaries change significantly by decade, the resulting irrigated areas may fall in widely differing areas from decade to decade. Finally, it must be remembered that these spatial extents were developed as an 'educated' guess and guide to better assign irrigated land to counties. The DO NOT represent confirmed areas of irrigation nor do they preclude irrigation activites elsewhere or at different scales.

2. "Potentially Reclaimed" land was derived from reclamation district boundaries selected based on formation dates or DWR Bulletin 27 data appropriate for the decade being analyzed. As these are , outside the Delta, based simply on formation dates there is no guarantee that reclamation activies occured to any large degree or at all.

The shapefile you requested is attached. Although every effort has been made to represent these data as completely and accurately as possible, it is important to note that this shapefile does not contain survey quality data. It was developed for illustrative purposes only and intended for use in small scale maps. This shapefile may contain information taken from representations or reproductions of data sources with incomplete or missing documentation. As such MWH cannot definitively determine accuracy of the data contained in the shapefile. The user should be aware that these data do not carry legal authority to define the boundaries or locations of fixed points.

attr.attrdef: Landcover classes derived from multiple sources cited in teh LGND_Srce field. Predominantly drawn from the geo-processed results of the Phyllis Fox work in 2015. (http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/19/4257/2015/) but supplemented with landcover from Kuechler (1977), reclamation district boundaries from Dept of Water Resources and Dept of Flood Management data sets as well as irrigated areas derived from USDA/CA Conservation Commission data from 1912 and USFS landcover representing 1934.

codesetd.codesets: Based either on USDA/CCC 1912 or USFS 1934 irrigated areas description. In both cases the irrigated area polygons were intersected with the decade-appropriate county boundaries and then iteratively reduced in size until the census reported aceages for that county and decade were reached to +-50 acres. This results in a couple of artifacts of which the user should be aware. Mainly, irrigated boundaries pull away from the county boundaries during this process. As county boundaries often follow hydrologic features, this results in an underrepresentation of irrigated land along such areas. Secondly, due to the fact that data are derived from a common source, but the county boundaries change significantly by decade, the resulting irrigated areas may fall in widely differing areas from decade to decade. Finally, it must be remembered that these spatial extents were developed as an 'educated' guess and guide to better assign irrigated land to counties. The DO NOT represent confirmed areas of irrigation nor do they preclude irrigation activites elsewhere or at different scales.

Results from an intersection of wetland categories (permanent wetland, seasonal wetland, vernal pools) and reclamation district boundaries selected based on formation dates or DWR Bulletin 27 data appropriate for the decade being analyzed. As these are based simply on formation dates, outside of the Delta there is no guarantee that reclamation activies occured to any large degree or at all.

attrdomv.udom: All other landcover classes are from Phyllis Fox (2015) or Kuechler (1977). http://www.hydrol-earth-syst-sci.net/19/4257/2015/. Please refer to this source documentation for full explanations and definitions.

attr.attrdef: Short reference to the source of the LEGEND landcover description.

Rim vs. Valley watershed as defined by UC Berkeley. The "VAL" portion being the primary study area. Due to some watershed induced wild diversions from a 'uniform' boundary, data were produced to cover the entire area both VAL and RIM.

Hydrologic Region name based on DWR CalWater 2.2 definition but modified to include entire extent of study area. The study area being defined by the Nat'l Hydrology Dataset waterhseds, differs slightly from the CalWater 2.2 sheds and so to eliminate splinters the region boundaries were expanded to include any study area data. Furthermore, the Legal Delta was intersect in as well to allow for the summarizing of acreages by hydrologic region, Legal Delta, and/or both.
Decade specific county boundaries to assist with tabular disaggregation of irrigated acreages by crop type in post-processing.
